Qt module:   qtmultimedia
Base tag:    v6.11.1 (qffmpegaudioframeconverter.cpp HEAD at the time of
             writing: 9a3c39ec39dfe375fe0d6e4008eb1c3cd5c8738d, 2026-03-31)
Applies to:  src/plugins/multimedia/ffmpeg/CMakeLists.txt,
             src/plugins/multimedia/ffmpeg/playbackengine/
               qffmpegaudioframeconverter.cpp,
             src/3rdparty/soundtouch/ (new, vendored)

Why: at large playback-rate stretch ratios, Qt's pitch compensation
(qffmpegaudioframeconverter.cpp's PitchShiftingAudioFrameConverter)
produces audible artifacts, but the FIRST version of this patch (pure
WSOLA via SoundTouch, replacing Qt's stock phase-vocoder entirely) only
traded one direction's problem for the other:

- Qt's original phase vocoder (Signalsmith Stretch, frequency-domain)
  sounds clean at 0.5x but produces audible vibrato/echo/"phasiness" at
  2x. Root cause: it reconstructs the signal by overlap-adding frames
  spaced by a synthesis hop = ratio * analysis hop. Speeding up (ratio <
  1) packs those frames CLOSER together in the output -- denser overlap
  means more simultaneous frames whose phases must stay coherent, which
  is what produces the phasiness/vibrato. Slowing down (ratio > 1)
  spreads frames further apart -- sparser overlap, less phase-coherence
  pressure, so it holds up well. (Signalsmith Stretch's own README says
  as much: "time-stretching sounds best for more modest changes (between
  0.75x and 1.5x)" -- it does not claim symmetric behaviour, and the
  dense-overlap-at-compression failure mode is inherently
  direction-dependent, not just "far from 1.0x".)
- Pure WSOLA (SoundTouch, time-domain, this patch's first version) has
  the OPPOSITE shape: clean at 2x, but at 0.5x produces a "sequence of
  split audio strips" with a buzz between them (reported directly by a
  user A/B against SMPlayer/mpv, which uses the same WSOLA family
  (scaletempo/scaletempo2) and shows the same artifact only much less
  severely). Root cause: speeding up only has to DISCARD redundant
  content -- there's an abundance of candidate splice points to
  cross-correlate against, a well-conditioned search. Slowing down has
  to REPEAT content to fill extra time; the splice point is chosen by
  cross-correlation alone (SoundTouch is plain WSOLA, not the
  pitch-synchronous PSOLA variant), so a repeated segment's boundary
  often doesn't line up with the signal's local pitch period -- audible
  as a buzz/seam at each repeat. Compounded by SoundTouch's own
  auto-tuning (TDStretch::calcSeqParameters()), which *enlarges* its
  analysis block at low tempo (90ms sequence at 0.5x vs 40ms at 2x)
  while keeping the overlap crossfade fixed at a constant 8ms
  (DEFAULT_OVERLAP_MS) regardless of tempo -- so the seam is
  proportionally more exposed at slow tempo.

Fix (this version, HYBRID): the two algorithms' failure modes are exact
mirror images of each other, so use each one only where it's strong.
makePitchShiftingAudioFrameConverter() now picks the concrete stretcher
based on direction: playbackRate >= 1.0 (speed-up) uses
WsolaPitchShiftingAudioFrameConverter (SoundTouch); playbackRate < 1.0
(slow-down) uses PhaseVocoderPitchShiftingAudioFrameConverter
(Signalsmith Stretch, restored to Qt's original, unmodified
implementation for this direction). Both classes implement the same
AbstractAudioFrameConverter interface used elsewhere in the file.
Signalsmith Stretch was never removed from the qtmultimedia tree by the
earlier version of this patch (only unused by this one file), so no
re-vendoring was needed -- CMakeLists.txt already carried its include
path from before. This dispatch is safe with no new machinery: the
audio renderer already reconstructs the frame converter from scratch on
every playback-rate change (AudioRenderer::onPlaybackRateChanged()
resets m_audioFrameConverter; initAudioFrameConverter() rebuilds it
lazily on the next frame), so there is no live mid-stream algorithm
switch to handle -- the choice is made once, at construction.

Status: VERIFIED WORKING end to end, 2026-07-18. An initial retest of
0.5x after this patch reportedly still produced the pure-WSOLA buzz/
strip artifact, which didn't match a line-by-line reading of the
dispatch code (the slow-down path is a byte-for-byte restoration of
Qt's original, unmodified PitchShiftingAudioFrameConverter, and the
>= 1.0f direction check matches the sign convention
TrivialAudioFrameConverter already uses elsewhere in this file: rate>1
= faster). Rather than guess further, added a one-line qWarning() in
makePitchShiftingAudioFrameConverter() that fires once per rate change
stating which concrete stretcher (WSOLA/SoundTouch vs phase vocoder/
Signalsmith Stretch) was actually selected for the current
playbackRate -- deliberately qWarning, not qDebug, since Vivace's own
qInstallMessageHandler (main.cpp) mirrors Warning/Critical/Fatal (not
Debug/Info) into vivace.log, and that handler is process-wide, so a
qWarning from Qt's own plugin code (loaded into the same process) is
captured there too with no Vivace-side changes needed. On rebuild +
retest, vivace.log showed the correct line ("pitch compensation using
phase vocoder (Signalsmith Stretch) for playbackRate=0.500") and the
user confirmed the 0.5x buzz was gone -- the earlier "not working"
report was against a stale/incomplete build, not a real code defect;
this hybrid dispatch is confirmed correct as written. The qWarning
diagnostic is left in place permanently (low-frequency -- once per
rate change, not per frame -- and consistent with this project's
existing instrumentation conventions, e.g. VIVACE_DVD_LOG). If the
crossover threshold (exactly 1.0x) turns out not to be the ideal split
point in some other case (e.g. borderline behaviour near 0.8x-1.2x),
it's a one-line constant to move in makePitchShiftingAudioFrameConverter().

Patch-fidelity note: the qtmultimedia repo's own top-level .gitignore has
a blanket "include" rule (matches any path component literally named
"include", not just a top-level one) that silently excluded
src/3rdparty/soundtouch/include/*.h (SoundTouch.h, FIFOSampleBuffer.h,
FIFOSamplePipe.h, STTypes.h, soundtouch_config.h) from a plain `git add -A`
-- those headers are present on disk but were missing from the first
regenerated patch. Re-added with `git add -f`; verified via `git apply
--check` against a clean baseline checkout of HEAD that the full patch
(including the include/ headers) applies cleanly with no conflicts.

To apply: cd <qtmultimedia source root> && git apply
patches/qtmultimedia-wsola-pitch-compensation.patch (or `patch -p1 <
...patch` if not a git checkout), then rebuild qtmultimedia (or all of
Qt) and Vivace.

